The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	 New Delhi: CWG gold medallist Somdev Dev Varman has been named in the squad for Asian Games to be held next month in Guangzhao, China.     
	With Leander Paes ruling himself out, the squad has Mahesh Bhupathi, Rohan Bopanna, Vishnu Vardhan, Karan Rastogi and Sanam K Singh.        
	London: Former England midfielder Paul Gascoigne (43) spent the night in police custody, after being arrested on suspicion of drugs offences, police sources said on Friday.         
	Nyon: Uefa has charged Barcelona goalkeeper Jose Pinto with improper conduct for allegedly whistling to fool a Copenhagen player into thinking he was offside during a Champions League game Wednesday.        
	Gangtok: State champions Sikkim Police managed to overpower local rivals Denzong Boyz 2-1, on Friday, and set up a pre-quarter final match against Lajong FC in the 32nd All India Governors Gold Cup football tournament being organised by Sikkim Football Association at Paljor Stadium.      
	Bad start  
	Las Vegas: Arjun Atwal and Jeev Milkha Singh had a sluggish start in the US PGA Shriners Hospital for Children Open, and risk missing the cut after turning in disappointing first round cards in the US $4.3 million tournament here.      
	Castellon: Jyoti Randhawa was the best placed Indian at tied 22nd after turning in a modest card of two-under 69 in the opening round of the Castello Masters golf tournament here, Friday.       
	Gagan honour  
	Chandigarh: Gagan Narang, who clinched four gold medals in Delhi Commonwealth Games, would be honoured by Haryana government at Sonipat on November 1, chief minister Bhupinder Singh Hooda Friday said.      
	Chennai: Chances of inclusion of squash as a sport in Olympic Games has brightened after the International Olympic Committee (IOC) shortlisted it for the 2020 edition, World Squash Federation (WSF) chief N.Ramachandran said Friday.         
	 Karachi: British newspaper, The Daily Telegraph, has apologised to former Pakistan captain Younis Khan for associating him with players agent and alleged bookmaker Mazhar Majeed. Younis lawyer Abdul Qayyum said the daily has published an apology regretting its story, linking Younis with Mazhar.        
	Lahore: In spite of the spot-fixing scandal, the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB)s chief operating officer Wasim Bari Friday predicted a brighter future for the country. We are now moving in the right direction and the focus of the players and people should now be on preparing for the 2011 World Cup, Bari said.                                                                                                                                                      
